Fixes #20890

#### `JQueryStatic.map`

Implemented the array collapsing and item filtering behaviors.

#### `JQueryStatic()`

`JQueryStatic()` now uses the argument passed in to determine the type parameter of the returned `JQuery` object.

Fixes #19597

Package express-socket.io-session is being used to provide session support for socket.io connections. Although SocketIO.Socket.handshake is in fact equal to Express.Request types definitions do not follow this properly. When using express-socket package it is doing type merging to inject session and sessionID to Express.Request but this injection do not affect SocketIO.Socket.handshake.

This Pull Request is changing SocketIO module by explicitly defining Handshake interface which allows doing further declaration merging. After that is is extending this Handshake interface in module express-socket.io-session just like module express-session is extending Expresss.Request.

This not the only way to achieving the desired effect but IMHO this solution is one of the cleanest ways of achieving it. I also though about changing express-session or even socket.io but this could lead to other problems.

title: Added href to SVGAttributes<T> for React
body:
I added an optional `href` property to `SVGAttributes<T>` in the index.d.ts file for React.

**Rationale**

According to [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/SVG/Attribute/xlink:href), `xlink:href` has been deprecated. The recommendation is to use `href` (without the namespace prefix) instead. 

This is a simple, non-breaking change. I've tested the fix in my application, and it worked. I'm not clear on how I would write a test for a simple string property. Also, I was unable to find a test for `xlinkHref` (the legacy version of `href`) to work from.

**Discussion**

It appears that, if you attempt to open a "naked" SVG file in a browser (I tested with Chrome), it will choke if the SVG contains `xlink:href`, even if the SVG file has a version number of 1.1 (which is an older version that _should_ require `xlink:href` and not support `href`). It will also choke in Microsoft PowerPoint (and presumably other Office apps).

For some reason, if the SVG is inline (i.e., embedded in an HTML file), rather than naked, the browser will allow `xlink:href`. Nonetheless, it's important to be able to use `href` to support the case where you want to export an SVG generated with a React app (e.g., an image editor) to a file.

**Example usage**

`<use href="#canvas" />`
